Title:     ECCO simplicity is easier than pro version.
             (Arabesque Software Inc.'s ECCO Simplicity 1.1 personal
             information management software)  (First Looks) (Brief
             Article)
Author:    Finnie, Scot


-------------------------------------------------------------------------
Full Text:

With a name like Simplicity, the new $149 "lite" version of Arabesque
Software's ECCO Professional sounds like PIM perfection. While ECCO 1.0
drew rave reviews last summer as a versatile and robust personal
information manager (First Looks, September 14, 1993), it didn't win much
praise for ease of use. ECCO's outline-based underpinnings provide
powerful cross-referencing and data portability, but the outline metaphor
isn't familiar to most PIM users, and the program provides so many views
that you're unlikely to feel comfortable with it right off.

Arabesque saw these drawbacks early on and responded with ECCO
Professional 1.1 and ECCO Simplicity 1.1. The goal for Simplicity was to
create a more accessible, more manageable PIM for people primarily
interested in address book and personal scheduling tools.

The best of ECCO Simplicity's new usability features are its graphical
weekly and monthly calendar views, which look like a Week-at-a-Glance
date book and a wall calendar, respectively. Drag-and-drop and right
mouse-button pop-ups are implemented extensively in these graphical views
and throughout the program--a marked improvement.

To get new users up and running faster, Simplicity installs a simplified
view that shows new larger toolbar icons with text labels. The toolbar
has only three buttons: Calendar, Phone, and Outlines. There are five
preconfigured outlines that ease the process of adapting to the outline
metaphor.

Simplicity also provides five template views customized to different
professions or tasks: Legal, Manager, Project, Research, and Sales.
Additional tweaks include sorting from any view and new Preferences
options for adjusting time slots in the calendar.

Fewer Features

What Simplicity doesn't have is ECCO Pro's optional Advanced menu
functions, which build user-created folders and columns. They let you
group and view outlines of all types, customize grid columns, and create
named filters for limiting the types of information shown in ECCO views.
You can upgrade to ECCO Pro 1.1 for $199.

Simplicity is much easier to use than the professional version, but it
isn't an all-new, greatly simplified PIM that blows away the competition
for ease of use. Although it has been significantly dressed up, the
powerful outline structure is still apparent in some parts of the
program. But overall, Arabesque was successful in making Simplicity much
less daunting to first-time users.

In addition to achieving its goal of being easier to use, Simplicity is
an excellent value at its $79 introductory price. Meanwhile, the $395
ECCO Professional 1.1 is absolutely first-rate. That's because
Simplicity's many usability enhancements come in the professional
version, too.

List price: ECCO Simplicity, Version 1.1, $149 ($79 through December
1993). Requires: 2MB RAM (4MB recommended), 3MB hard disk space, Windows
3.1. Arabesque Software Inc., 2340 130th Ave. NE, Bellevue, WA 98005;
800-457-4243, 206-885-4272; fax, 206-885-0127.
